                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d497">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">103.9169/3430a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in Sweden</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-05-02T20:00:00-04:00"
                            >May 2, 1944—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>808. From Department and FEA. Reference your 1525, April 29.<note n="41"
                        xml:id="d497fn1">Not printed.</note> We do not feel that presentation at
                    this time of your proposed note <pb facs="0540" n="530" xml:id="pg_530"/> on
                    Bothnian traffic<note n="42" xml:id="d497fn2">See telegram 1352, April 19, 5
                        p.m., from Stockholm, <ref target="#pg_510">p. 510</ref>.</note> would
                    jeopardize the attainment of our other objectives. It might, in fact, strengthen
                    our position by further indicating to Swedes our doubts as to the advantages of
                    the War Trade Agreement in view of their performance under it. You are therefore
                    requested to present the proposed note with British concurrence. [Department and
                    FEA.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
